04239nam a22006735i 9780231555968DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222022nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2021045737  a97802315559687 a10.7312/roqu205342doi  a(DE-B1597)627244  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aHM851b.R6647 2021 4aHM851b.R6647 2022 7aCOM0710002bisacsh04a006.80952223/eng/202112071 aRoquet, Paul, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Immersive Enclosure :bVirtual Reality in Japan /cPaul Roquet. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource :b25 b&w image stills  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction: The Ambient Power Play -- t1. ACOUSTICS OF THE ONE-PERSON SPACE -- t2. TRANSLATING THE VIRTUAL INTO JAPANESE -- t3. VR TELEWORK AND THE PRIVATIZATION OF PRESENCE -- t4. IMMERSIVE ANXIETIES IN THE VR ISEKAI -- t5. VR AS A TECHNOLOGY OF MASCULINITY -- tCONCLUSIO -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlthough virtual reality promises to immerse a person in another world, its true power lies in its ability to sever a person’s spatial situatedness in this one. This is especially clear in Japan, where the VR headset has been embraced as a way to block off existing social environments and reroute perception into more malleable virtual platforms. Is immersion just another name for enclosure?In this groundbreaking analysis of virtual reality, Paul Roquet uncovers how the technology is reshaping the politics of labor, gender, home, and nation. He examines how VR in Japan diverged from American militarism and techno-utopian visions and became a tool for renegotiating personal space. Individuals turned to the VR headset to immerse themselves in three-dimensional worlds drawn from manga, video games, and genre literature. The Japanese government promised VR-operated robots would enable a new era of remote work, targeting those who could not otherwise leave home. Middle-aged men and corporate brands used VR to reimagine themselves through the virtual bodies of anime-styled teenage girls. At a time when digital platforms continue to encroach on everyday life, The Immersive Enclosure takes a critical look at these attempts to jettison existing social realities and offers a bold new approach for understanding the media environments to come.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aVirtual realityxEconomic aspectszJapan. 0aVirtual realityxIndustrial applicationszJapan. 0aVirtual realityxSocial aspectszJapan. 0aVirtual realityzJapanxPsychological aspects. 7aCOMPUTERS / Digital Media / Video & Animation.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311074966340uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/roqu2053440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231555968423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231555968/original  a978-3-11-074966-3  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_CHCOMSGSEN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CHCOMSGSEN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK